    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Kafka at Guantánamo</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Steven Girshick letter compares procedures for administering hearings for detainees at Guantanamo to something from Kafka (Mar 24 article)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Guantánamo Detainees Make Their Case'' (news article, March 24):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Guantánamo Detainees Make Their Case'' (news article, March 24):</p>
        <p>You report that Capt. Eric Kaniut of the Navy, chief administrator of the hearings for detainees currently taking place at the Guantánamo prison camp, states that the new proceedings ''are just like a parole board.''</p>
        <p>So the detainees, not having been convicted of anything, are facing a parole board: a scenario worthy of Kafka.</p>
        <p>Steven Girshick  Minneapolis, March 25, 2005</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
